{{ infobox website | name = [[Image:Logo xobdo.png|160px|Logo of XOBDO]] | screenshot = [[Image:Xobdo screen.PNG|280px|XOBDO's index page]] | caption = Screenshot of XOBDO's welcome page | url = http://xobdo.in/ | commercial = No | type = [[Online dictionaries|Online Dictionary]] | language = 28 | registration = Optional | owner = An [[Online community|Online Community]] | author = Bikram M. Baruah}}
'''Xobdo.org''' is the first online [[Assamese language|Assamese]] dictionary to become available online on March 10, 2006.<ref>[http://www.assamtribune.com/apr2406/State.html] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060519140059/http://www.assamtribune.com/apr2406/State.html |date=May 19, 2006 }}</ref> As of August 6, 2011 the database of this dictionary contains 37013 words of Assamese language. This is a [[wiki]], where anybody can contribute and edit words in the dictionary provided they have a substantial knowledge of the Assamese language. Moreover, the dictionary has the facility to categorize the words as per their origin, nature and locality. It also has the facility of incorporating encyclopedic entries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xobdo.org/dic/index.php?w=Jayanta%20Hazarika&l=1 |title=Jayanta Hazarika (English) |publisher=Xobdo.org |date=2008-01-04 |accessdate=2012-12-19}}{{dead link|date=July 2015}}</ref> This [[website]] uses [[UNICODE]] fonts which ensures global visibility of Assamese fonts when users set their [[character encoding]] option to [[UTF-8|Unicode (UTF-8)]].
The dictionary is the brainchild of Bikram M Baruah,<ref>{{cite web|author=TI Trade |url=http://www.assamtribune.com/scripts/details.asp?id=jun1408/at08 |title=The Assam Tribune, June 14, 2008 |publisher=Assamtribune.com |date=2008-06-14 |accessdate=2012-12-19}}</ref> an [[Assamese people|Assamese]] [[Petroleum engineering|petroleum engineer]] based in [[Abu Dhabi]]. Later lots of interested people specialized in different areas joined as the working force behind this dictionary.
In 2007 xobdo.org added multiple interfaces to include 17 more languages spoken in the [[North East India]]: [[Khasi language|Khasi]], [[Dimasa language|Dimasa]], [[Bodo language|Bodo]], [[Karbi language|Karbi]], [[Nagamese]], [[Garo language|Garo]], [[Mongsen Ao language|Ao]], [[Mizo language|Mizo]], [[Mishing language|Mishing]], [[Apatani language|Tanii (Apatani)]], [[Monpa language|Monpa]], [[Meitei-lon]], [[Bishnupriya]], [[Chakma language|Chakma]], [[Kokborok|Kok-Borok]], [[Kukish languages|Kuki]], and [[Tanchangya language|Tanchangya]]{{which|date=October 2011}} aimed at giving a multilingual edge to the dictionary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/story/349364.html |title=Indian Express, August 16, 2008 |publisher=Indianexpress.com |date=2008-08-16 |accessdate=2012-12-19}}</ref> Currently XOBDO gives a platform for 27 languages of North-East India, along with English. However, the database for these languages is still substantially small.
==Authorship and management== [[Image:xobdoideabase.png|200px|thumb|right|Database Architecture of xobdo.org]] A group of volunteers are responsible for adding words at XOBDO database. As of now the website has two levels of volunteers: "contributors" and "editors". A contributor enters an [[English language|English]] and its corresponding Assamese word to the temporary database. Afterwards an editor assigns a unique "idea ID" to the corresponding English and Assamese words and carries on other editing works, if required, to match the standards of XOBDO. After assigning the idea ID the words are added to the main database ready to be retrieved by a user.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xobdo.org/dic/mod/article/index.php?aid=5 |title=XOBDO's Policy |publisher=Xobdo.org |date= |accessdate=2012-12-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115064502/http://www.xobdo.org/dic/mod/article/index.php?aid=5 |archivedate=January 15, 2013 |df= }}</ref>
==Technical details== Initially xobdo.org employed [[Microsoft]] server tools and technologies. It ran [[Active Server Pages|ASP]]s on [[Windows]] [[Internet Information Services|IIS]] and the primary database on [[RDBMS]] based on [[Microsoft SQL Server]]. However, in 2007it moved to [[open source]] technology and started running [[PHP]]s on [[Apache HTTP Server|Apache]] and an [[RDBMS]] on [[MySQL]].
